# Core Coding Standards

## Principles (in priority order)
1. **Functional correctness** over performance optimization
2. **DRY** — extract shared logic into utilities; never duplicate > 3 lines
3. **Single Responsibility** — one function/class does one thing
4. **Explicit over implicit** — no magic; name things clearly
5. **Fail fast** — validate inputs at boundaries, throw early

## Naming
- Files: `kebab-case.ts` for modules, `PascalCase.ts` for classes/scenes
- Variables/functions: `camelCase`
- Constants: `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`
- Types/interfaces: `PascalCase`, prefix interfaces with `I` only if ambiguous
- Booleans: prefix with `is`, `has`, `can`, `should`

## Functions
- Max 30 lines per function; extract if longer
- Max 3 parameters; use an options object beyond that
- Pure functions preferred — minimize side effects
- Always specify return types on exported functions

## Error Handling
- Never swallow errors silently
- Use typed error classes for domain errors
- Always log errors with context before re-throwing

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
try { doThing(); } catch (e) {}

// ✅ GOOD
try {
  doThing();
} catch (error) {
  logger.error("Failed to do thing", { error, context });
  throw new GameError("Thing failed", { cause: error });
}
```

## Code Quality Gates
- **80% test coverage** minimum (lines + branches)
- No `any` types without a `// eslint-disable` comment explaining why
- No `console.log` — use the project logger (see logging rule)
- No commented-out code in commits
